&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Hi Jeff, 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Well I don&#39;t know about the exact implementations of HyperNEAT you
&gt;&gt;&gt; are
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; using (note that P-NEAT is just NEAT with additive mutations
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; disabled), but in principle crossover should choose genes randomly
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; from both parents as it builds the offspring genome, the child. In
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; HyperNEAT the crossover is different, there you actually do a
&gt;&gt;&gt; regular
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; NEAT evolution of networks that build other networks based on the
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; substrate configuration. That is, you only mate and mutate the
&gt;&gt;&gt; CPPNs.
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; But in the case you get lots of individuals with equal fitness, I
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; guess these individuals are clones. Perhaps the code frequently
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; chooses the same individuals for mating? You can try to avoid this
&gt;&gt;&gt; by
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; introducing a loop in which you try candidates for a &quot;father&quot; that
&gt;&gt;&gt; are
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; not compatible with the mother, that is, when their compatibility
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; distance is 0.00, try again. There is another possibility, simply
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; every mutation disturbs the CPPN and therefore the produced
&gt;&gt;&gt; network is
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; changed in such a magnitude that is has no chance for survival and
&gt;&gt;&gt; is
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; discarded. Even though there is speciation.
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Peter
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
