&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; --- In neat@yahoogroups.com, Jeff Clune &lt;jclune@&gt; wrote:
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Hello all-
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Does crossover do anything in PNEAT and HyperNEAT?
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; PNEAT:
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; If I am reading the code correctly, during crossover, if the
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; substrates are
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; the same (i.e. all links have the same ID), which is always the
&gt;&gt;&gt; case
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; in
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; P-NEAT, *all* of the link values are taken from either parent1 or
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; parent2.
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Isn&#39;t it more normal when crossing over to take some from parent1
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; and some
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; from parent2? Why grab all from just one?
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; This means that in PNEAT crossover does nothing, right? It will
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; always grab
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; the substrate of parent1 or the substrate of parent2.  If I track
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; parent and
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; offspring fitness, 100% of the time the child has the exact same
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; fitness as
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; one of the two parents.
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; On to HyperNEAT:
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; I tracked the fitness of each parent and the resulting offspring.
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; The odd
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; thing is that the organisms that are crossed only (i.e. they are
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; never
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; mutated) have the *exact* same fitness of one of their parents
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 98.88% of the
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; time. In 20 runs, that was only 136 orgs out of 12257 that were
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; crossed over
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; and not mutated. That seems wrong, doesn&#39;t it? Why would these
&gt;&gt;&gt; new
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; links
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; have such a small impact? It turns out that this is because
&gt;&gt;&gt; nearly
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; every
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; time that there is an extra link that gets placed in the child,
&gt;&gt;&gt; the
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; parent
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; that donated that link is also the parent whose weights are being
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; grabbed,
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; meaning that the crossover is only copying the parent (hence the
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; same
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; fitness). It seems to me that crossover should be much more
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; disruptive, no?
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; As a final test, I did a set of hyperneat and pneat runs with the
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; default
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; &#39;MutateOnlyProbability&#39; parameter set to .25, so 25% of orgs
&gt;&gt;&gt; never
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; are
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; candidates for crossover. I then ran experimental treatments
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; hyperneat-noCross and pneat-noCross where the
&gt;&gt;&gt; MutateOnlyProbability
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; parameter was set to 1, so no orgs were crossed over. Despite my
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; comments
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; above, Hyperneat (with cross) did beat HyperNEAT-noCross, however
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; the
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; difference was not tremendous (although it does seem to be
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; statistically
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; significant). For p-neat, the reverse was true. Nevertheless,
&gt;&gt;&gt; this
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; is not a
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; perfect test of whether crossover pays dividends, because if
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; crossover does
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; nothing most of the time, and I increase MutateOnlyProbability
&gt;&gt;&gt; from
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; .25 to
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 1, I have effectively raised the mutation rate (only 80% of
&gt;&gt;&gt; crossed
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; orgs are
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; also mutated).
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Are these the intended consequences of crossover, or am I missing
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; something?
